[normal]&#xa0;[bold]AFS0074[bold]Written evidence submitted by the Anti Academies Alliance (AAA)[bold]1. Introduction[bold]1.1 The Anti Academies Alliance is a national campaign group that supports local campaigners
[normal] opposed to academy conver
[normal]sion. (More details about our work can be found at 
[normal]www.antiacademies.org.uk
[normal] )
[normal]. Whilst we have views on 
[normal]all 
[normal]the questions asked in the terms of reference
[normal], we have chosen to focus on 2 main
[normal] points raised with u
[normal]s by local parents
[normal] in recent weeks
[normal]. These relate mainly to the process of academy conversion – forced or ‘voluntary’.
[normal] We have included 
[normal]3 
[normal]appendices which are 
[normal]reports/statement
[normal]s relating to
[normal] recent academy conversion processes. We have included them 
[normal]with som
[normal]e editing and with names redacted
[normal].
[normal] They are the thoughts of b
[normal]usy parents
[normal] often working without adequate information. Their voices should be heard.
[normal]1.2 The AAA remains opposed to academy conversions. We are not opposed to schools – once they have become aca
[normal]demies. We want every school to flourish. Howeve
[normal]r 
[normal]we continue to reject the political ideology that lies behind academy conversion – voluntary or forced. In essence academy conversion is about a ‘supply-side revolution’
[normal] (a
[normal]s the 2009 Tory party manifesto 
[normal]noted). It seeks to open up the public sector to private interests. Yet there remains no credible evidence that this leads to sustained improvement in schools. Th
[normal]us th
[normal]e Secretary of State’s political ideology is trumping evidence based policy. It is aliena
[normal]ting parents and staff, but worse still it threatens 
[normal]the best interest of this and future 
[normal]generation
[normal]s of children
[normal].
[normal] The sobering experience of two decades of market driven reforms in Sweden should be 
[normal]enough to
[normal] persuade the government to halt these reforms. 
[normal]Regrettably, the Coalition is unwilling to listen at the moment. We hope the Select Committee can help make them take note.
