[normal]3[bold]. The process for approving, compelling and establishing academies and free schools, including working with sponsors [bold]3
[normal].1 
[normal]Our second concern relates 
[normal]to the
[normal] process for approving, compelling and establishing academies and free schools, including working with sponsors
[normal]. The current process is undemocratic, dismissive of other stakeholder views and a centrally co
[normal]ntrolled – rather than locally-
[normal]controlled pr
[normal]ocess.
[normal]3
[normal].2 
[normal]T
[normal]he Secretary of State
[normal] is riding roughshod over the views of 
[normal]local 
[normal]stakeholders rather than seeking to ‘win’ an educational argument by engaging in genuine consultation and democratic decision making. There is a presumption that academy conversi
[normal]on is always the best solution. The 
[normal]manner in which unaccountable brokers pressurise governors to ‘opt for’ academy status has been described to us as like having a ‘gun put to your head’. 
[normal]In these cases, ‘forced’ academy conversion becomes ‘voluntary’. As
[normal] the process lacks both genuine accountability and any transparency, parents are often suspicious of the conversion process.
[normal]3
[normal].3 
[normal]Academy conversion can actually be a distraction
[normal] for school improvement
[normal]. 
[normal]The time and effort of meeting brokers and potential s
[normal]ponsors can ta
[normal]ke the school leadership away from
[normal] the vital task of improving teaching 
[normal]and 
[normal]learning. 
[normal]3
[normal].4 
[normal]There are also concerns about the way Interim Executive Boards (IEBs) are used. It seems that they are sometimes populated with employees/representativ
[normal]es of the proposed sponsors. We believe this creates potential conflicts of interest over the decision to convert.
[normal] Similarly there 
[normal]is 
[normal]concern
[normal] that academy chains are cherry picking certain 
[normal]schools 
[normal]for ‘takeover
[normal]’. Sometimes i
[normal]t appears 
[normal]that 
[normal]it is not always 
[normal]the schools that are most in need of improvement but schools that are already improving
[normal] that become academies
[normal]. 
[normal] Whilst sponsor can choose whether to take over a school – schools cannot choose whether or not to be taken over. 
[normal]3
[normal].5 
[normal]Finally there are concerns about the experience, viability and accountability of academy chains. There a huge numbers of new chains. Often these are single individual head teachers who ‘morph’ into chains by taking over a couple of local school. They becom
[normal]e executive heads and some label themselves CEOs. Their focus becomes building the business. In other cases foreign venture capital lies behind
[normal] head teachers, former council and government education officers. They combine to create companies that have very
[normal] little public face and seemingly no accountability to local people or OFSTED.
[normal]3.6 
[normal]In light of these concerns, the AAA would like to make the following r
[normal]ecommendations: 
[normal]We believe the
[normal] Select committee should urge the government to
[normal] take immediate steps to:
[normal]December 2013
